</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="119" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Hemichoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemichoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Hemichoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares diagnostic morphological characters with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Zelomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelomorpha" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Zelomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except: notauli absent, mesoscutum lacking distinct lobes; gena greatly produced posteroventrally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="119" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">
Members of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Hemichoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemichoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Hemichoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are, like 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Zelomorpha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Zelomorpha" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Zelomorpha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, koinobiont endoparasitoids of late instar lepidopteran larvae. The solitary wasp larva emerges from the prepupal larva after it has spun its cocoon, and spins its own cocoon inside the host cocoon next to the cadaver.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="119" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Restricted to the New World, known from Mexico to Argentina.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="119" type="species richness">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Species richness.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="119">
Including the three species described here, there are eight described species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Braconidae" genus="Hemichoma" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hemichoma" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="119">Hemichoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
